name: Multimap
comment:
An associative container that maps a key to multiple values.

Key lookups return mutable collections that are views of the multimap. Updates to the multimap are reflected in these collections and similarly, modifications to the returned collections are reflected in the multimap.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no key in the multimap.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one key in the multimap.

length.name: length
length.comment: The number of keys in the multimap.

[].comment: Returns the values for the given quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.[].key. An empty iterable is returned if quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.[].key is not mapped. The returned collection is a view on the multimap. Updates to the collection modify the multimap and likewise, modifications to the multimap are reflected in the returned collection.

add.name: add
add.comment: Adds an association from the given key to the given value.

addAll.name: addAll
addAll.comment:
Adds all associations of quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.addAll.other to this multimap.

The operation is equivalent to doing this[key] = value for each key and associated value in other. It iterates over quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.addAll.other, which must therefore not change during the iteration.

addValues.name: addValues
addValues.comment: Adds an association from the given key to each of the given values.

containsKey.name: containsKey
containsKey.comment: Returns whether this multimap contains the given quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.containsKey.key.

containsValue.name: containsValue
containsValue.comment: Returns whether this multimap contains the given quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.containsValue.value.

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment:
Applies quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.forEach.f to each {key, value} pair of the multimap.

It is an error to add or remove keys from the map during iteration.

forEachKey.name: forEachKey
forEachKey.comment:
Applies quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.forEachKey.f to each {key, Iterable<value>} pair of the multimap.

It is an error to add or remove keys from the map during iteration.

remove.name: remove
remove.comment: Removes the association between the given quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.remove.key and quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.remove.value. Returns true if the association existed, false otherwise.

removeAll.name: removeAll
removeAll.comment: Removes the association for the given quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.removeAll.key. Returns the collection of removed values, or an empty iterable if quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.removeAll.key was unmapped.

toMap.name: toMap
toMap.comment: Returns a copy of this multimap as a map.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of quiver/quiver-collection.Multimap.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.
